snippet.textDisplay: When serious critics like Mark praise TLJ for being "daring" or "challenging", I just despair. The problem wasn't the story that TLJ tried to tell - it was the abysmal execution. The trilogy may very well feel like it doesn't have a middle episode because TROS threw out TLJ's plot threads, but Rian did something similar by ending most of TFA's plot threads in jarring and completely unsatisfying ways, and then started crowing about his talent for "subverting expectations" and laughing at people who were invested in the story he was supposed to be continuing. The Disney trilogy consists of three terrible stories told by two insufferable hacks: one who hit the reset button on the entire setting in order to create a string of nostalgic moments connected by massive and utterly contrived coincidences, and another who placed vague themes over consistency and logic for the sake of emotional payoffs which, consequently, felt completely unearned.

snippet.textDisplay:
Totally agreed. 

The Last Jedi was an attempt to democratise The Force by suggesting that it wasn’t just an inheritance of lineage, but that anybody could have it flowing through them. At times the plotting was clumsy, but there was a through-line with the story and theme and it provoked thought. 

Rise of Skywalker is an attempt to checklist everything the fans wanted and airbrush out anything controversial about The Last Jedi. The storyline is driven by that and, for me, there was just a sense of ho-hum when it’s all over.

snippet.textDisplay:
(I'm my forties, grew up loving star wars - escapism from bullies, being from quite a poor family etc - and I've always loved it) It's so nice to hear Mark Kermode who knows more than pretty much anyone Bout films say he likes The Last Jedi and likes it more every time he sees it. I love TLJ, I think it is the most well thought-out star wars film with clever themes running through it, really interesting Universe-expanding story points as well as being very much a proper star wars film.

I watched RoS yesterday and agree with Kermode on that too. I really enjoyed it because I always watch Star Wars with childhood wonder in my mind first and foremost. There was a lot to like about. When I analysed it afterwards, there's a lot wrong with it too but it's really entertaining in many ways and isn't that the point of films?! TLJ is a much better film but RoS is a good star wars film and I'm looking forward to seeing it again.

snippet.textDisplay:
Gotta disagree regarding Last Jedi ... It RUINED ANY tiny fragments of hope this trilogy had in terms of MAYBE being a success ... People might deny it now, but MOST fans thought Force Awakens was a solid start ... and there were interesting directions the story could be taken. BUT ... RJ KILLED any mystery Ray had ... He RUINED Luke ... He made Snoke POINTLESS ... He just forgot about The Knights of Ren ... and by the end of the movie, the story had little direction or built up excitement, heading into the final chapter of a trilogy!
JJ SHOULD have written and directed all three films ... and if he had I'm convinced we would have been left with a slightly more enjoyable saga with FAR better pacing.
